{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_25","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md <<'EOF'\n# Page Flows Research\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Use publicly accessible flow references first (support docs, official help pages, and public app documentation), then comparable flow narratives from app previews/walkthroughs.\n- Do not copy proprietary screenshots, exact layouts, UI copy, iconography, brand systems, or assets.\n- Do not include secrets, tokens, credentials, private keys, session values, cookies, or environment variables.\n- Any flow captures used in this document are text-only references; any raw asset references are marked \"'`private_only=true`.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. Alarmy homepage and feature overview: https://alar.my/en\n2. Alarmy mission configuration support: https://alarmy-android.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360004242254--Mission-How-can-I-set-the-missions-math-shake-etc\n3. Alarmy wake-up check support: https://alarmy-ios.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/900000085346--WakeUpCheck-I-don'\"'t-understand-how-Wake-up-check-works-Give-me-an-explanation\n4. Alarmy mission strategy article: https://alar.my/en/blog/how-to-choose-alarmy-mission\n5. Habitica mobile task workflow: https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Mobile_App_for_iOS%3A_Habitica\n6. Habitica setup tasks: https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Setup_Tasks\n7. Sleep as Android quick start: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/faqs/quick_start.html\n8. Sleep as Android smart wakeup + error handling: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/smart_wake_up.html\n9. Sleep as Android awake detection and tracking error recovery: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/awake_detection.html\n\n## Flow References\n\n### Reference 1: Alarmy mission-linked alarm offloading\n\n- Product: Alarmy\n- Source URL or description: Alarmy feature and FAQ content on the official site plus support FAQ\n- Flow name: Wake alarm -> mission completion -> dismissal state progression\n- Screen types: onboarding, create_edit, active_task, completion\n- Observed transitions: The user sets an alarm and attaches a mission in the alarm editor. When the alarm fires, the primary control is mission completion rather than a blind swipe/tap dismiss path. The app remains in an active mission state until completion, then moves to dismissed state. If fallback check is enabled, it transitions into a delayed verification state before final completion.\n- Empty/error states: If the user does not answer the post-dismissal check, the dismissed alarm revives and re-enters active state. The system also gates some mission types behind premium and limits free users to one mission per alarm, which creates a paywall/feature-denied branch.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep mission-like, explicit task-gated completion for high-friction moments so users cannot accidentally pass a critical action. Preserve a short visible confirmation path from set -> active -> verified-complete.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not hide completion behind implicit auto-dismiss behavior. Do not block users unexpectedly with confusing mission-count restrictions without surfacing clear affordances first.\n- Raw Asset Privacy: no new screenshots were captured in this stage; content evidence is textual and not reusable UI artifacts; no proprietary asset reuse.\n\n### Reference 2: Alarmy wake-up check verification loop\n\n- Product: Alarmy\n- Source URL or description: Alarmy iOS support article \\\"WakeUpCheck\\\" flow details\n- Flow name: Dismissal -> no-response countdown -> verification popup -> either success or revive\n- Screen types: active_task, completion\n- Observed transitions: Alarm rings and is dismissed into lock/wait state. After the configured delay, a silent check notification appears. Opening the app enters a confirmation state with a binary action (\"'`Yes, I am up!`). Failure to answer before timeout transitions directly back to ringing alarm.\n- Empty/error states: Empty/idle gap states are meaningful (`notification waiting`, `red icon off`), and silence-based prompts indicate verification is inactive state. Primary failure path is timeout, which explicitly restarts mission/alarm.\n- what_to_adapt: Use a two-stage completion model for critical high-salience tasks: primary action + delayed verification with clear recovery path for false positives.\n- what_not_to_copy: Avoid adding punitive messaging during confirmation. Keep prompts deterministic, not ambiguous; avoid silent state changes users cannot recover from.\n- Raw Asset Privacy: no screenshots captured locally for this reference; private flow notes only and `private_only=true`.\n\n### Reference 3: Alarmy mission selection and progressive complexity\n\n- Product: Alarmy\n- Source URL or description: Alarmy mission setup and mission strategy article\n- Flow name: Mission assignment strategy -> optional chain configuration -> wake execution\n- Screen types: create_edit, onboarding, active_task\n- Observed transitions: Users choose mission categories, set a mission in the alarm editor, and can optionally chain multiple missions into a sequence. The flow supports progressive complexity (single mission first, then multi-step chain if needed) and preserves a simple first-run path before introducing advanced combinations.\n- Empty/error states: The article implies that single-mission fatigue can trigger routine adaptation; no explicit crash/error state, but it highlights travel/special-location exceptions requiring alternate mission routes.\n- what_to_adapt: Adopt gradual complexity: start with one action state and unlock chain complexity only after success persistence. Keep alternatives for context-sensitive failures (e.g., location unavailable).\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not force immediate multi-step complexity on first use. Avoid requiring users to configure full mission systems before hearing/handling first alarm.\n- Raw Asset Privacy: public flow notes only; no private screen captures collected, `private_only=true`.\n\n### Reference 4: Habitica tabbed task creation and completion lifecycle\n\n- Product: Habitica\n- Source URL or description: Habitica mobile iOS workflow and setup pages\n- Flow name: Starter setup -> tab-based task creation -> check/completion -> history visibility via streak metadata\n- Screen types: onboarding, home, create_edit, active_task, completion, history_streaks, profile_settings\n- Observed transitions: New users receive initial life-area guided setup and receive starter tasks. The task tab model uses a persistent tab shell (Habits/Dailies/To Do/Rewards/Menu), with + actions opening modal forms. Task creation saves via a dedicated Create action; subsequent open/edit/delete actions are reachable from task detail screens. Completion applies immediate task state updates, while profile/settings are managed via menu and notification/settings paths.\n- Empty/error states: The docs describe state regressions when a completed To Do is unchecked (state rolls back and rewards/XP are lost), which defines an important undo-like recovery edge. Streak counters are displayed in Dailies, which implies a history state branch for continuity and accountability.\n- what_to_adapt: Preserve a predictable tab shell for frequently used operations and surface edit/delete/recover actions close to created content. Use explicit state rollback language for destructive transitions.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not overcomplicate task creation with many secondary steps before a first successful object creation. Do not auto-trigger irreversible state transitions without explicit action feedback.\n- Raw Asset Privacy: no captured screenshots from this run are used; text references only, `private_only=true`.\n\n### Reference 5: Sleep as Android onboarding, alarm scheduling, and fault handling\n\n- Product: Sleep as Android\n- Source URL or description: Sleep as Android quick start + smart wakeup + error handling docs\n- Flow name: First-run setup -> alarm scheduling -> tracking + smart wake transitions -> runtime anomaly recovery\n- Screen types: onboarding, home, create_edit, active_task, completion, profile_settings\n- Observed transitions: First-run flow is intentionally reduced to alarm creation (`+` icon, time pickers, DONE), then optional smart wakeup window and sleep-tracking activation. Morning flow includes alarm ring presentation and reporting transitions into wake-phase detail. The document explicitly defines fallback paths for alarm timing and alarm sound issues.\n- Empty/error states: Explicit error handling includes alarms ringing at unexpected times, ringtone load failures, missing selected files/storage permissions, system restrictions disabling tracking, and low-battery behavior. These transitions preserve user safety by defining diagnosis + next actions and backup behavior.\n- what_to_adapt: Use a minimal first-run path for complex sleep/wake apps, then progressively expose advanced controls. Define explicit diagnostics for common failures and deterministic fallback actions.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not bury permission/permission-failure messaging behind ambiguous generic errors. Avoid exposing too many default options before core flow trust is established.\n- Raw Asset Privacy: no local flow captures were generated in this pass; this evidence is text documentation and `private_only=true`.\n\n## Screen Type Coverage\n\n- onboarding: Sleep as Android quick start and Alarmy first-time setup descriptions provide clear staged onboarding.\n- home: Alarmy and Sleep as Android home/landing states are documented as persistent daily/schedule entry points.\n- create_edit: Alarmy mission setup and Sleep as Android alarm editor flows provide explicit create/edit states.\n- active_task: Alarmy mission execution and WakeUpCheck verification states are strong references.\n- completion: Alarmy mission completion + verification + post-complete reporting states.\n- history_streaks: Habitica Dailies expose streak context for completion history; explicit multi-day continuity surface.\n- profile_settings: Habitica menu and Sleep as Android support/settings paths define profile/settings handling.\n- paywall_subscription: Alarmy FAQ and mission descriptions imply premium-gated capabilities and free-tier constraints.\n\n## Transition And State Patterns\n\n- Gated action-to-complete pattern: alarm/task actions remain in an active state until explicit completion criteria are met.\n- Delayed verification pattern: high-risk completion events include a short grace/verification phase before commit.\n- Progressive disclosure pattern: reduced first-run flows that add advanced settings later improve completion for critical wake flows.\n- Retry-or-revive pattern: timeout or missed verification does not end the flow; it re-enters an earlier high-salience state.\n- Failure-recovery pattern: each source with a mission/alarm flow defines a direct recovery action (retry mission, reopen settings, check permissions, use fallback tone, check system restrictions).\n- State rollback pattern: completed state can be reversed in some task systems; users need explicit confirmation and consequence visibility before and after rollback.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Keep a simple core wake flow with progressive complexity: one default path first, advanced mission/chaining controls later.\n- Keep state transitions explicit and visible (`active` -> `pending confirm` -> `complete`) for mission-like or high-friction interactions.\n- Add a verification checkpoint for mission success where false positives are likely, with clear timeout recovery.\n- Surface settings and permission recovery paths from error states without leaving the user in ambiguous limbo.\n- Preserve task and streak history semantics only if they are understandable at glance; avoid deep history screens behind uncertain navigation.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not mirror exact Alarmy or Habitica layouts, brand copy, iconography, or spacing.\n- Do not require users to configure a full mission/advanced alarm stack before first successful completion.\n- Do not copy unclear premium gating or hard lockouts where alternative actions are absent.\n- Do not hide critical fallback behavior (revive/retry paths) behind background logic that users cannot recover from.\n- Do not overfit sleep-tracking complexity to this app if flow data indicates users benefit from lighter first-run scaffolding.\n\n## Raw Asset Privacy\n\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-pack.json`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.last-message.md`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n  - private_only: true\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`\n  - private_only: true\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
