{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_35","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"mkdir -p /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/pageflows_research/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research && cat > /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/pageflows_research/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md <<'EOF'\n# Page Flows Research\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Use publicly accessible flow references first (support docs, official help pages, and public app documentation), then comparable flow narratives from product pages and walkthroughs.\n- If no page-flow capture exists for a specific screen, mark that gap explicitly and avoid inferring private or exact proprietary layouts.\n- Do not copy proprietary screenshots, exact copy, iconography, brand systems, or asset files.\n- Do not include secrets, tokens, session IDs, credentials, or environment values.\n- All captured raw assets referenced here are marked \"'`private_only=true`.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. Alarmy feature and app overview: https://alar.my/en\n2. Alarmy mission setup support: https://alarmy-android.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360004242254--Mission-How-can-I-set-the-missions-math-shake-etc\n3. Alarmy wake-up check support: https://alarmy-ios.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/900000085346--WakeUpCheck-I-don'\"'t-understand-how-Wake-up-check-works-Give-me-an-explanation\n4. Alarmy mission strategy article: https://alar.my/en/blog/how-to-choose-alarmy-mission\n5. Habitica iOS task workflow: https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Mobile_App_for_iOS%3A_Habitica\n6. Habitica setup tasks: https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Setup_Tasks\n7. Sleep as Android quick start: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/faqs/quick_start.html\n8. Sleep as Android smart wakeup behavior: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/smart_wake_up.html\n9. Sleep as Android awake detection and recovery: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/awake_detection.html\n\n## Flow References\n\n### Reference 1: Alarmy mission-linked dismissal flow\n\n- product: Alarmy\n- source URL or description: Alarmy homepage and FAQ context combined with mission strategy article\n- flow name: Set alarm with mission -> alarm fires -> mission required for dismissal\n- screen types: onboarding, create_edit, active_task, completion\n- observed transitions: User sets an alarm and assigns a mission in the alarm editor. Alarm fires and presents an action path that requires completing the configured mission before the alarm can be dismissed. Mission behavior remains active across wake sequence states until task completion.\n- empty/error states: Free users are limited in mission options and mission count; premium capability introduces additional mission types. This creates an access-control branch that must be surfaced clearly so users are not blocked without path guidance.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep the dismissal flow deterministic and explicit: mission completion should feel meaningful and impossible to bypass by default during initial wake attempt.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not copy exact mission UI, iconography, or exact step order.\n- raw asset notes: no new screenshots captured locally; evidence is text-only; private_only=true.\n\n### Reference 2: Alarmy WakeUpCheck delayed verification\n\n- product: Alarmy\n- source URL or description: Alarmy iOS support article on WakeUpCheck\n- flow name: Dismiss -> wait for check window -> silent check notification -> confirm wake state -> final completion or revive\n- screen types: active_task, completion, create_edit\n- observed transitions: After dismissing a mission or alarm, app enters a delayed verification state. The app notifies user again without sound after timeout and opens a confirm popup for wakefulness. Confirming success completes dismissal; failing to confirm restarts the alarm.\n- empty/error states: Timeout/no-response state explicitly returns to alarm (revive ring), which is a clear failure-recovery transition.\n- what_to_adapt: Add a deliberate verification checkpoint for important wake/mission moments and make timeout behavior obvious and recoverable.\n- what_not_to_copy: Avoid silent state transitions that users cannot identify; keep a clear message and escape path.\n- raw asset notes: no new screenshots captured locally; evidence is text-only; private_only=true.\n\n### Reference 3: Alarmy mission choice and progression strategy\n\n- product: Alarmy\n- source URL or description: https://alar.my/en/blog/how-to-choose-alarmy-mission\n- flow name: Choose mission type -> optional chaining -> fallback reassessment\n- screen types: onboarding, create_edit, active_task, completion\n- observed transitions: Users are encouraged to start with one mission and later chain multiple missions when one becomes too easy. Categories evolve from cognitive/physical/location missions. Flow progression is iterative: install -> choose -> execute -> adapt -> iterate.\n- empty/error states: Explicit fallback path for exceptional contexts (travel or unavailable photo/barcode references) indicates need for alternate mission route instead of hard failure.\n- what_to_adapt: Use staged complexity and provide contextual mission replacement options when environmental preconditions break assumptions.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not force multi-step chained missions during onboarding; avoid overwhelming first-time setup.\n- raw asset notes: no new screenshots captured locally; evidence is text-only; private_only=true.\n\n### Reference 4: Habitica seeded onboarding and task lifecycle\n\n- product: Habitica\n- source URL or description: https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Setup_Tasks and https://habitica.fandom.com/wiki/Mobile_App_for_iOS%3A_Habitica\n- flow name: Startup guided setup -> tab shell -> create/edit -> completion and history cues\n- screen types: onboarding, home, create_edit, active_task, completion, history_streaks, profile_settings\n- observed transitions: On first launch, setup assigns starter tasks by chosen life area, establishing a baseline flow. Main navigation uses task-type tabs; creation opens a dedicated add screen. Completed task state and history/streak context appear on task views; menu/settings paths are separated from active task screens.\n- empty/error states: Task systems describe explicit reversal semantics (for example unchecking completed items returns to active and restores prior state costs), which is a non-trivial state transition to avoid unexpected reward debt and surprise.\n- what_to_adapt: Preserve predictable tabbed entry points and show state-change consequences before irreversible actions.\n- what_not_to_copy: Avoid dense task creation flows and hidden consequences that make users uncertain about completion/reversal.\n- raw asset notes: no new screenshots captured locally; evidence is text-only; private_only=true.\n\n### Reference 5: Sleep as Android first-run simplification and fault recovery\n\n- product: Sleep as Android\n- source URL or description: https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/faqs/quick_start.html, https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/smart_wake_up.html, https://sleep.urbandroid.org/docs/sleep/awake_detection.html\n- flow name: First setup -> alarm scheduling -> smart wakeup/permissions -> ongoing alarm and tracking recovery paths\n- screen types: onboarding, home, create_edit, active_task, profile_settings\n- observed transitions: Users move from alarm setup into running tracking, then to smart wake scheduling states, and into daily report output. If tracking/alarm behavior degrades, users move into permission or diagnostics states and retry with guided checks.\n- empty/error states: Alarm timing mismatch, missing permissions, storage and service errors, background restrictions, and low battery are all explicitly handled with actionable diagnostic paths.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep first-run setup minimal, then progressively expose advanced controls with clear defaults and diagnostics.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not expose advanced alarm/diagnostic options before users complete a trusted baseline path.\n- raw asset notes: no new screenshots captured locally; evidence is text-only; private_only=true.\n\n## Screen Type Coverage\n\n- onboarding: covered via Alarmy/ Sleep as Android setup references\n- home: covered via Alarmy and Sleep as Android home/main screens and Habitica tab entry model\n- create_edit: covered via Alarmy mission/mission-edit flow and Sleep as Android alarm editing\n- active_task: covered by Alarmy mission execution and WakeUpCheck verification\n- completion: covered by mission-complete and timeout recovery patterns\n- history_streaks: covered via Habitica streak/task history cues\n- profile_settings: covered via Habitica menu/settings and Sleep as Android system/permission paths\n- paywall_subscription: covered by Alarmy premium vs free mission gating\n\n## Transition And State Patterns\n\n- Task-locked wake completion: key user action must satisfy a completion condition before moving out of active alarm state.\n- Verification checkpoint: optional delayed-confirm pattern reduces false-complete outcomes.\n- Timeout/restart loop: failure to confirm wake state or mission completion triggers explicit alarm revival/restart transitions.\n- Progressive complexity: onboarding starts with single-step defaults, with optional sequencing and complexity added after repeat success.\n- Diagnostics-before-blocking: recovery branches for permissions/alarms errors appear before hard stops.\n- State visibility: reversal and consequence states (for example completed-task rollback or mission failure) should be explicit rather than implicit.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Use a simple default wake/task setup with clear expansion to advanced options.\n- Keep wake completion gated by one primary high-friction action.\n- Preserve explicit verification for actions that can be falsely completed.\n- Preserve rollback and recovery paths, especially for timeout and permission failures.\n- Separate operational state flows from settings and profile actions to reduce accidental taps.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not replicate exact visual layout or copy proprietary branding from these references.\n- Do not force users into advanced chain complexity before first successful completion.\n- Do not hide verification/timeout behavior.\n- Do not make profile/account actions compete with critical wake-task controls.\n- Do not ignore system-level failure states and send users to opaque dead-ends.\n\n## Raw Asset Privacy\n\n- source: comparison pack and research pipeline files referenced in this stage\n  - \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-pack.json` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.last-message.md` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json` -> private_only: true\n  - `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` -> private_only: true\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
